Breast cancer in older women: trends in diagnosis.

Rybolt AH(1), Waterbury L.

Author information:
(1)University of Tennessee, College of Medicine, Chattanooga.

Breast cancer is a disease of elderly as well as middle-aged women. Even in 
patients of advanced age, breast cancer shortens life expectancy. Early 
diagnosis, through preventative screening with mammography and physical 
examination, offers the best hope of cure. Deterrents to use of mammography have 
included radiation risk, unnecessary biopsies, and cost. However, current low 
radiation doses minimize radiation risks; test specificity is much better in 
older women, leading to fewer unnecessary biopsies; and new Medicare guidelines 
lower out-of-pocket patient cost. With increased education of older women and 
health care providers, methods to decrease mortality from breast cancer in the 
elderly can become widespread.

